{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530458"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:06:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:06:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14545"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14545"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.05,0.17,0.56,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7238"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114406"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7238"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14545"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96407"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4656"},{"type":"tags","id":"4669"},{"type":"tags","id":"4784"},{"type":"tags","id":"4789"},{"type":"tags","id":"4817"},{"type":"tags","id":"9663"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17583"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47894"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114406"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of rectal pain, purulent rectal discharge and itching. He is sexually active with multiple partners, has receptive anal sex and does not use condoms consistently. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. There are small excoriation marks around the anus, though it appears otherwise normal. On gentle pressure around the anus there is tenderness and a small amount of yellowish purulent discharge is released. Anoscopy is performed and whilst there is discomfort, erythema of the rectal walls and discharge, there are no obvious lesions or ulcers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA rectal swab is taken and sent for microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the likely microscopic appearance of the causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gram-positive cocci in clusters","Gram-variable pleomorphic rods","Gram-positive diplococci in chains","Gram-negative diplococci","Spirochaetes visible under dark-field microscopy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs suggestive of proctitis, likely secondary to a sexually transmitted infection (STI). Given his age, sexual history, and the presence of purulent rectal discharge, gonorrhoea is a highly probable cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E, the causative organism of gonorrhoea, is a \u003Cstrong\u003Egram-negative diplococci\u003C/strong\u003E. These bacteria typically appear as pairs of kidney-shaped cocci (diplococci) that stain pink (Gram-negative) and are often seen inside neutrophils (intracellular). This characteristic appearance on Gram stain of rectal or urethral discharge can provide a rapid presumptive diagnosis of gonorrhoea in symptomatic men.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGram-positive cocci in clusters\u003C/strong\u003E is the typical appearance of \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus\u003C/em\u003E species, which are not commonly associated with STIs or proctitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGram-variable pleomorphic rods\u003C/strong\u003E might describe the appearance of organisms like \u003Cem\u003EGardnerella vaginalis\u003C/em\u003E, which is associated with bacterial vaginosis rather than proctitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGram-positive diplococci in chains\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus\u003C/em\u003E species. Perianal cellulitis can be caused by streptococci, however this is typically seen in children and the perianal skin would be erythematous and moist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpirochaetes visible under dark-field microscopy\u003C/strong\u003E describes the appearance of \u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E, the causative organism of syphilis. While syphilis is an important STI to consider, it typically causes ulcers or lesions around the anus or in the rectum as opposed to discharge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst nucleic acid amplification tests (NAATs) are now the gold standard for diagnosing gonorrhoea, it is important to be aware of the microbiological appearance of common pathogens. Swabs sent for culture are important in the workup of gonorrhoea as there is an increasing incidence of antibiotic resistance, and culture and sensitivities should be tested. In patients presenting with proctitis, empiric treatment should be started whilst awaiting results. Treatment with doxycycline, ceftriaxone and valaciclovir is recommended, in order to cover potential chlamydia, gonorrhoea and herpes infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gonorrhoea is a common cause of proctitis and urethritis in men who have sex with men.","Neisseria gonorrhoeae appears as intracellular Gram-negative diplococci on microscopy.","Rectal swab and first-void urine are appropriate samples for diagnosing gonorrhoea in men who have sex with men."],"references":["Sigle GW, Kim R. Sexually transmitted proctitis. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2015 Jun;28(2):70-8. doi: 10.1055/s-0035-1547334. PMID: 26034402; PMCID: PMC4442722. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4442722/#:~:text=gonorrhea)%20is%20a%20gram%2Dnegative,may%20be%20present%20on%20occasions.","Davis TW, Goldstone SE. Sexually transmitted infections as a cause of proctitis in men who have sex with men. Dis Colon Rectum. 2009 Mar;52(3):507-12. doi: 10.1007/DCR.0b013e31819ad537. PMID: 19333054. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19333054/","Anorectal syndromes | STI Guidelines Australia [Internet]. Available at: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/syndromes/anorectal-syndromes/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96407"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14545"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96407"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-16T13:06:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-16T13:07:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7238"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114406"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings",